{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: request-builder -> API client payload. A unit test of only a formatter could miss dropped labels at wiring time (MOCK-MISS). No real OS/network/subprocess is required because an in-process fake client can capture the outbound payload (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=no). Correctness does not depend on model output content (b=no) and there is no multi-agent sequence (c/d=no). Rejected System/Agentic because behavior text is about request fields, not live transport or model judgment.","test_description":"Wire classifier with a fake API client that records requests. Invoke classify() with a known taxonomy and assert the outbound request contains every taxonomy label exactly as expected.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure appears at response-handling boundary: provider response -> validation -> public return value. A pure unit test of normalization alone may miss wiring where raw provider value is forwarded (MOCK-MISS). In-process stubbed provider response is sufficient; no real OS/network/subprocess needed (a=no). No dependence on real model quality/output variability (b=no), no multi-step agent chain (c/d=no). Rejected Agentic/System because behavior text focuses on guardrail mapping logic for an unexpected label.","test_description":"Use a fake provider that returns an out-of-taxonomy label (e.g., \"medical\"). Call classify() and assert returned label is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is explicitly local deterministic transformation (\"normalization step\" with \"identical raw API responses\"). No module interaction is required to surface the failure, so Unit is the floor. Rejected Integration because the behavior text disqualifies boundary-dependent failure: same input -> same normalized output is function-level determinism.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixtures (case/whitespace/synonym variants held constant per fixture) and assert identical output label every run.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.88,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires live model calls and consistency of model-produced labels over repeats, so correctness depends on real AI output/non-determinism (LLM-DEP=yes). A stub would always pass and hide provider/model drift (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Workflow because this is repeated single-step classification calls, not a multi-stage agent pipeline with sequential model decisions.","test_description":"Run N repeated real classification calls for the same input; log raw provider responses and final labels. Assert label changes only when corresponding provider response content changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is local policy logic: token counting and truncate/reject decision before send. This can be caught at function/object boundary without real I/O. Rejected Integration because behavior text is about \"request construction enforces\" budget rule itself, not cross-module transport behavior.","test_description":"Given over-budget and within-budget documents, test request-construction policy function/object directly and assert truncate/reject/allow outcomes and resulting token counts match config.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.23,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Needs real external API usage accounting; in-process fakes can mask provider tokenizer/accounting differences (REAL-INFRA=yes, MOCK-HIDE=yes). Correctness here is infrastructure/accounting, not model decision quality, so Agentic is not strictly required by behavior text (deterministic-assertion trap avoided: this is not output-quality validation). Rejected Integration because behavior says \"provider-reported token usage\" which requires real provider report.","test_description":"Execute real API calls with representative documents and capture provider-reported usage fields. Assert reported tokens <= configured budget for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.23,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is retry orchestration across modules (API client error -> backoff policy -> retry -> return). Stubbed client responses (e.g., rate-limit then success) can reproduce this exactly, so real OS/network is not required (INTEGRATION-BRAKE a=no). No dependence on model output content (b=no), no chained multi-agent reasoning (c/d=no). Rejected System because behavior text is control-flow handling of a known signal, testable with deterministic in-process fakes.","test_description":"Use fake provider/client that returns rate-limit error on first call and success on second; use controllable clock/sleeper. Assert module waits per policy, retries, and returns successful label instead of surfacing error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
